1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:03,791
The detention happened at our shop

2
00:00:04,000 --> 00:00:06,250
In Ras al-Kour we had a shop, a barbershop

3
00:00:07,250 --> 00:00:08,666
The detention happened there

4
00:00:10,083 --> 00:00:12,583
A car with three men arrived, a car from the <i>Hisba</i>

5
00:00:14,458 --> 00:00:16,333
They got out, and I was standing in the street

6
00:00:17,583 --> 00:00:21,208
They arrested me on the spot, took my phones, searched me, and brought me to this place

7
00:00:22,458 --> 00:00:24,916
Interviewer: Was there an informant against you?

8
00:00:25,083 --> 00:00:27,791
Yes, there was a clue, but no proof

9
00:00:29,083 --> 00:00:30,916
In the end

10
00:00:32,916 --> 00:00:34,916
He said, We just want any proof against you

11
00:00:35,000 --> 00:00:36,625
And as for the rest, we know how to deal with you

12
00:00:36,666 --> 00:00:39,625
Interviewer: When they came to arrest you, did they come asking for you by name?

13
00:00:39,750 --> 00:00:40,750
Or was there more than one person?

14
00:00:40,916 --> 00:00:42,208
No, me personally

15
00:00:42,708 --> 00:00:44,583
Interviewer: So there was an informant against you?

16
00:00:44,666 --> 00:00:48,083
Yes, there was some tip, but I don’t know what it was

17
00:00:48,375 --> 00:00:51,791
Interviewer: Was it someone you knew, or one of your friends?

18
00:00:52,000 --> 00:00:56,000
Or someone you dealt with in your life through work?

19
00:00:56,166 --> 00:00:59,000
Honestly, there was a young man, and he’s gone now

20
00:00:59,208 --> 00:01:01,375
We had some problems between us, and he was killed in the shelling

21
00:01:02,083 --> 00:01:06,875
After some time, after the liberation, they said that so-and-so, son of so-and-so, was the one

22
00:01:07,000 --> 00:01:09,916
Who informed, and he had a car, and that kind of thing

23
00:01:10,583 --> 00:01:12,791
And he worked transporting people

24
00:01:14,125 --> 00:01:19,333
Interviewer: When did they bring you to this prison? Was it at <i>maghreb</i> [sunset], <i>isha</i> [evening], or at noon?

25
00:01:19,416 --> 00:01:20,625
No, no, at <i>maghreb</i>

26
00:01:21,375 --> 00:01:24,291
Between <i>asr</i> [afternoon] and <i>maghreb</i>, and it was raining

27
00:01:24,625 --> 00:01:29,166
Interviewer: The three people you mentioned. Were they from Mosul or from outside Mosul?

28
00:01:29,208 --> 00:01:31,375
No, their driver was from Mosul

29
00:01:32,000 --> 00:01:33,958
A young man named Mahmoud, and we

30
00:01:34,166 --> 00:01:37,166
And the other two, one was thin and dark-skinned, tall

31
00:01:37,500 --> 00:01:40,375
He was from the countryside or something like that

32
00:01:40,750 --> 00:01:43,041
He wasn’t from Mosul, but the driver was from Mosul

33
00:01:44,208 --> 00:01:45,375
From his accent and the way he spoke
